&lt;p&gt;
In this case we get 8 possibilities. More generally, for &lt;i&gt;n&lt;/i&gt; digits we can count from \(0\) to \(2^n - 1\) for a total of \(2^n\) numbers so the total number of subsets of a set with &lt;i&gt;n&lt;/i&gt; elements is \(2^n\).
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
